# Pattern: ZITADEL Login v2 — force it instance-wide

ZITADEL ships two login UIs. The new **Login v2** (the separate
`zitadel-login` deployment, served under `/ui/v2/login`) is the one to use.
Force it on for the whole instance so every flow — including external-IdP
callbacks — uses the same, predictable URLs.

This is identity content: set it via the **API or the console**
(Instance → Features), never in git (invariant 6).

## Force Login v2 on the instance

```bash
# requires the operator PAT — see runbooks/zitadel-identity-via-api.md
zreq -X PUT /v2/features/instance -d '{
  "loginV2": {
    "required": true,
    "baseUri": "https://id.{{ domain }}/ui/v2/login"
  }
}'
```

(Or: console → Instance → Features → Login v2 → required, with the same base
URI.) After this, all human login goes through `/ui/v2/login`.

## External-IdP callback URL differs by login version

When you register {{ community_name }} as a client in an **external** provider
(Google, etc.), the redirect/callback URL you whitelist there depends on which
login version is active:

- **Login v2** (what we force above):
  `https://id.{{ domain }}/idps/callback`
- **Login v1** (legacy, for reference):
  `https://id.{{ domain }}/ui/login/login/externalidp/callback`

Register the **v2** URL in the external provider. Registering the wrong one is
the most common cause of `redirect_uri_mismatch` on the provider side.

## Determine the exact redirect_uri programmatically

Do not guess — ask ZITADEL what redirect_uri it will use for a given IdP by
starting an IdP intent:

```bash
zreq -X POST /v2/idp_intents -d '{
  "idpId": "<idp-id>",
  "urls": {
    "successUrl": "https://{{ domain }}/",
    "failureUrl": "https://{{ domain }}/login-error"
  }
}'
# the response's authUrl / the provider exchange reveals the exact redirect_uri
```

Use that exact value when registering the client in the external provider.

